**Q6. The string "PAYPALISHIRING" is written in a zigzag pattern on a given number of rows like this: (you may want to display this pattern in a fixed font for better legibility)**


1.First I looked at the problem and thought about how the printed pattern looked like it would be mapped out on a matrix. I wrote out the number of "main" columns and then the number of "middle" columns.
```
P           I         N
A      L    S     I   G
Y    A      H    R
P           I
------------------------
4     2     4     2   2(*)
```
The last line is 2 only because the word ends, but we can see that the pattern is 4-2-4-2-4-.... When drawing it out for numRows = 3, the pattern became

```
P         A         H         N
A    P    L    S    I    I    G
Y         I         R
---------------------------------
3    1    3    1    3    1    2(*)
```
Again we can see the pattern is 3-1-3-1-3-...

So the pattern of "main" rows to "mid" rows is n, n-2, n, n-2, ...

When I tried to build an algorithm for this pattern I got stuck. How would I make the index move up n, then down n-2 without confusing myself or missing edge cases.

**CODE:**
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
✅ **Java Code** :
**Runtime:**  2 ms, faster than 100.00% of Java online submissions for Zigzag Conversion.
```
class Solution {
    public String convert(String s, int numRows) {
    if(numRows==1) return s;
    int x = 2 * (numRows-1); 
    int len = s.length();
    char[] c = new char[len];
    int k =0;
    for(int i=0; i < numRows; i++)
    {
        for(int j=i;j<len;j=j+x)
        {
            c[k++] = s.charAt(j);
            if(i>0 && i<numRows-1 && j+x-2*i < len)
            {
                   c[k++] = s.charAt(j+x-2*i); 
            }
        }
    }
    return new String(c);
}
}

```
